Wilson recalls she bought poor boys clothes to go to school.

“I figure if they have clothes to wear, they can go to school. If they have no shoes, they were not going anywhere. But if they had clothes, they could go to the mission,” she remembered.

A native of St Livatte near Belmont, she taught in St Andrew (1951-1954) but got married the next year.

However, when she got a letter saying she still owed $15.75 on her school fees, she quit her job. She had met and decided to marry her husband, while a teacher. While married, Wilson taught homemaking classes in the first Grammar School in the city.
